<subSubSection id="9E99656AFFBAFFB234A0FAEE93809029" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="354" pageId="6" pageNumber="353" type="description">
<paragraph id="D63C36E1FFBAFFB334A0FAEE92A196B5" blockId="6.[151,1437,1359,2021]" pageId="6" pageNumber="353">
<emphasis id="E4F7EAF3FFBAFFB334A0FAEE952E9439" bold="true" box="[199,530,1359,1384]" pageId="6" pageNumber="353">
Description. 
<typeStatus id="09388843FFBAFFB33505FAEE96F39439" box="[354,463,1359,1384]" pageId="6" pageNumber="353">Holotype</typeStatus>
male
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="4EB82A64FFBAFFB33644FAEE95459439" box="[547,633,1359,1384]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–42" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1903,1925]" captionTargetBox="[144,1429,268,1837]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[144,1429,268,1837]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 37–42. Chvalaea Papp &amp; Földvári. Habitus. 37. Chvalaea amazonica Ale-Rocha, 2006, holotype ♀; 38. Chvalaea annularis sp. nov., holotype ♂; 39. Chvalaea boliviana Ale-Rocha, 2006, paratype ♀; 40. Chvalaea catarinensis Ale-Rocha, 2006, paratype ♂; 41. Chvalaea ecuadoriensis sp. nov., paratype ♂. 42. Chvalaea masneri Ale-Rocha, 2006, paratype ♀. Scale bars = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612725/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="353">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
). Body length: 5.7 mm. Wing length: 5.3 mm. 
<emphasis id="E4F7EAF3FFBAFFB330FBFAEE93DE9439" bold="true" box="[1180,1250,1359,1384]" pageId="6" pageNumber="353">Head.</emphasis>
Frons broad (at mid-length about as wide as width of anterior ocellus), as long as 1/6 of face length (
<figureCitation id="4EB82A64FFBAFFB33010FAD093F094D8" box="[1143,1228,1393,1418]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–14" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1149,1171]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,623,1127]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[188,1398,623,1127]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 13–14. Chvalaea Papp &amp; Földvári. 13–14. Frons. 13. Chvalaea ecuadoriensis sp. nov.; 14. Chvalaea masneri Ale- Rocha; Scale bar = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612713/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="353">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Antenna brown; postpedicel about 1.5 times length of scape and pedicel combined, with dense brown microtrichia and 1 short, thin dorsal seta near base; stylus arista-like, about 1.5 times length of scape, pedicel and postpedicel combined; 1 pair of ocellar setae very short, proclinate. Proboscis brown and very short; palpus covered with dense yellow microtrichia and long, slender setae. 
<emphasis id="E4F7EAF3FFBAFFB335C9FA579532975E" bold="true" box="[430,526,1526,1551]" pageId="6" pageNumber="353">Thorax.</emphasis>
Covered with sparse reddish brown pruinosity, paler, almost yellow on pleura. Pronotum brown. Pleura yellow, except anepisternum and katepisternum brown. Scutellum pale brown with 1 pair of long, strong convergent apical setae, and 1 thin very short lateral seta, about 1/3 length of apical pair. Acrostichals and dorsocentrals uniserial, very short, slender and sparse on scutum; notopleuron with 1 long, strong seta, with 10 shorter, slender setae; 1 very short, slender anterior postalar seta, with 1 anterior [lost in 
<typeStatus id="09388843FFBAFFB33154F9DA92A497C5" box="[1331,1432,1659,1684]" pageId="6" pageNumber="353">holotype</typeStatus>
, slender in 
<typeStatus id="09388843FFBAFFB33572F93F96BF97E7" box="[277,387,1694,1718]" pageId="6" pageNumber="353">paratypes</typeStatus>
] and 1 posterior postalar seta [lost in 
<typeStatus id="09388843FFBAFFB3372AF93D948E97E4" box="[845,946,1692,1717]" pageId="6" pageNumber="353">holotype</typeStatus>
, strong in 
<typeStatus id="09388843FFBAFFB33052F93F939B97E7" box="[1077,1191,1694,1718]" pageId="6" pageNumber="353">paratypes</typeStatus>
]. 
<emphasis id="E4F7EAF3FFBAFFB330DAF93D923897E4" bold="true" box="[1213,1284,1692,1717]" pageId="6" pageNumber="353">Wing.</emphasis>
Pale brown; pterostigma brown, elongate, narrow; cell dm slightly shorter than basal cells; cell cua slightly shorter than half cell bm; CuA+CuP not reaching wing margin; vein M 
<subScript id="4A0734A4FFBAFFB336A3F94F95F097AD" attach="left" box="[708,716,1774,1788]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="353">1</subScript>
evanescent, vein M 
<subScript id="4A0734A4FFBAFFB337CBF94F948897AD" attach="left" box="[940,948,1774,1788]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="353">4</subScript>
reaching wing margin (
<figureCitation id="4EB82A64FFBAFFB330D8F97E922897A9" box="[1215,1300,1759,1784]" captionStart="FIGURES 45–52" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1529,1551]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,450,1499]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,447,1507]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 45–52. Chvalaea Papp &amp; Földvári. Wings. 45. Chvalaea amazonica Ale-Rocha, 2006, holotype ♀; 46. Chvalaea annularis sp. nov., holotype ♂; 47. Chvalaea boliviana Ale-Rocha, 2006, paratype ♀; 48. Chvalaea catarinensis Ale-Rocha, 2006, paratype ♂; 49. Chvalaea ecuadoriensis sp. nov., paratype ♂; 50. Chvalaea masneri Ale-Rocha, 2006, paratype ♀; 51. Chvalaea pulchra Ale-Rocha, 2006, holotype ♀; 52. Chvalaea sinclairi sp. nov., holotype ♂. Abbreviations: bm = basal medial cell; br = basal radial cell; cua = anterior cubital cell; CuA+CuP = anterior branch of cubital vein + posterior branch of cubital vein; dm = discal medial cell; M 1 = first branch of media; M 4 = fourth branch of media; R 1 = anterior branch of radius; R 2+3 = second branch of radius; R 4+5 = third branch of radius. Scale bars = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612729/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="353">Fig. 49</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="E4F7EAF3FFBAFFB33140F97E926397A9" bold="true" box="[1319,1375,1759,1784]" pageId="6" pageNumber="353">Legs</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="4EB82A64FFBAFFB33109F97E978A964D" captionStart="FIGURES 37–42" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1903,1925]" captionTargetBox="[144,1429,268,1837]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[144,1429,268,1837]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 37–42. Chvalaea Papp &amp; Földvári. Habitus. 37. Chvalaea amazonica Ale-Rocha, 2006, holotype ♀; 38. Chvalaea annularis sp. nov., holotype ♂; 39. Chvalaea boliviana Ale-Rocha, 2006, paratype ♀; 40. Chvalaea catarinensis Ale-Rocha, 2006, paratype ♂; 41. Chvalaea ecuadoriensis sp. nov., paratype ♂. 42. Chvalaea masneri Ale-Rocha, 2006, paratype ♀. Scale bars = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612725/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="353">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
). Extensively brown, except coxae yellow and femora pale brown near base, gradually darkened to brown apically. Chaetotaxy: fore tibia with 1 long and thin posteroventral seta at mid-length; mid tibia with 1 long and strong dorsal seta near base, 2 anterior on basal half and 2 anterior on apical half, 2 long posteroventral setae, with 1 on basal fourth and 1 on apical half; mid femur with 1 anterior seta on distal two-thirds; hind tibia with 2 long, thin anteroventral setae and 2 long, thin posteroventral setae on basal half; fore and mid tarsomere 1 with 1 ventral seta long and stronger near base; hind tarsomere 1 with 2 series of elongate black spine-like setae, with 5 anteroventral and 2 posteroventral near apex; hind tarsomeres 3–5 with short, blunt, black spine-like ventral setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D63C36E1FFBBFFB234F0FF36946D9006" blockId="7.[151,1437,151,776]" pageId="7" pageNumber="354">
<emphasis id="E4F7EAF3FFBBFFB234F0FF36962F91E1" bold="true" box="[151,275,151,176]" pageId="7" pageNumber="354">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Black, slender, slightly curved upwards, sides almost parallel in lateral view. 
<typeStatus id="09388843FFBBFFB230E5FF3993D891E1" box="[1154,1252,152,176]" pageId="7" pageNumber="354">Paratype</typeStatus>
male terminalia (
<figureCitation id="4EB82A64FFBBFFB234F8FF18961A9180" box="[159,294,185,210]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–32" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1786,1808]" captionTargetBox="[151,1431,225,1690]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,220,1732]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 27–32. Chvalaea ecuadoriensis sp. nov. 27–30. Male terminalia (Paratype), phallus highlighted in gray. 27. Hypandrium and epandrium, ventral view; 28. Epandrium with cerci, dorsal view; 29. Hypandrium and epandrium, left lateral view; 30. Hypandrium and epandrium, right lateral view. 31–32. Female terminalia (Paratype). 31. Dorsal view; 32. Ventral view. Abbreviations: sur = surstylus; cerc = cercus; ST = sternite; T = tergite. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612721/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="354">Figs 27–30</figureCitation>
): similar to 
<taxonomicName id="11834D62FFBBFFB235D2FF1895089180" authorityName="Ale-Rocha" authorityYear="2006" box="[437,564,185,209]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Chvalaea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="masneri">
<emphasis id="E4F7EAF3FFBBFFB235D2FF1895089180" box="[437,564,185,209]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="354">C. masneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="11834D62FFBBFFB23615FF1894239180" authorityName="Ale-Rocha" authorityYear="2006" box="[626,799,185,209]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Chvalaea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="catarinensis">
<emphasis id="E4F7EAF3FFBBFFB23615FF1894239180" box="[626,799,185,209]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="354">C. catarinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, hypandrium narrow, distal margin sub-triangular with round apex and 2 long subapical setae (
<figureCitation id="4EB82A64FFBBFFB23600FF7B958391A2" box="[615,703,218,243]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–32" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1786,1808]" captionTargetBox="[151,1431,225,1690]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,220,1732]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 27–32. Chvalaea ecuadoriensis sp. nov. 27–30. Male terminalia (Paratype), phallus highlighted in gray. 27. Hypandrium and epandrium, ventral view; 28. Epandrium with cerci, dorsal view; 29. Hypandrium and epandrium, left lateral view; 30. Hypandrium and epandrium, right lateral view. 31–32. Female terminalia (Paratype). 31. Dorsal view; 32. Ventral view. Abbreviations: sur = surstylus; cerc = cercus; ST = sternite; T = tergite. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612721/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="354">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
); subepandrial sclerite with anterior margin rounded and apical margin strongly concave (
<figureCitation id="4EB82A64FFBBFFB235A0FF5D951C9045" box="[455,544,252,277]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–32" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1786,1808]" captionTargetBox="[151,1431,225,1690]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,220,1732]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 27–32. Chvalaea ecuadoriensis sp. nov. 27–30. Male terminalia (Paratype), phallus highlighted in gray. 27. Hypandrium and epandrium, ventral view; 28. Epandrium with cerci, dorsal view; 29. Hypandrium and epandrium, left lateral view; 30. Hypandrium and epandrium, right lateral view. 31–32. Female terminalia (Paratype). 31. Dorsal view; 32. Ventral view. Abbreviations: sur = surstylus; cerc = cercus; ST = sternite; T = tergite. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612721/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="354">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
); hypoproct with broad, nearly triangular indentation at mid-width of apical margin (
<figureCitation id="4EB82A64FFBBFFB2349FFEBC96739067" box="[248,335,285,310]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–32" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1786,1808]" captionTargetBox="[151,1431,225,1690]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,220,1732]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 27–32. Chvalaea ecuadoriensis sp. nov. 27–30. Male terminalia (Paratype), phallus highlighted in gray. 27. Hypandrium and epandrium, ventral view; 28. Epandrium with cerci, dorsal view; 29. Hypandrium and epandrium, left lateral view; 30. Hypandrium and epandrium, right lateral view. 31–32. Female terminalia (Paratype). 31. Dorsal view; 32. Ventral view. Abbreviations: sur = surstylus; cerc = cercus; ST = sternite; T = tergite. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612721/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="354">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="E4F7EAF3FFBBFFB23502FEBC96F89067" bold="true" box="[357,452,285,310]" pageId="7" pageNumber="354">Female.</emphasis>
Similar to male. Female terminalia: resembling 
<taxonomicName id="11834D62FFBBFFB23790FEBF93A89064" authorityName="Ale-Rocha" authorityYear="2006" box="[1015,1172,286,309]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Chvalaea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis id="E4F7EAF3FFBBFFB23790FEBF93A89064" box="[1015,1172,286,309]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="354">C. amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with sternite 8 broad, triangular; tergite 8 with notch on lateral margin (
<figureCitation id="4EB82A64FFBBFFB236A6FE9F94789006" box="[705,836,318,343]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–32" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1786,1808]" captionTargetBox="[151,1431,225,1690]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,220,1732]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 27–32. Chvalaea ecuadoriensis sp. nov. 27–30. Male terminalia (Paratype), phallus highlighted in gray. 27. Hypandrium and epandrium, ventral view; 28. Epandrium with cerci, dorsal view; 29. Hypandrium and epandrium, left lateral view; 30. Hypandrium and epandrium, right lateral view. 31–32. Female terminalia (Paratype). 31. Dorsal view; 32. Ventral view. Abbreviations: sur = surstylus; cerc = cercus; ST = sternite; T = tergite. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612721/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="354">Figs 31–32</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D63C36E1FFBBFFB234A0FEFE93809029" blockId="7.[151,1437,151,776]" box="[199,1212,351,376]" pageId="7" pageNumber="354">
<emphasis id="E4F7EAF3FFBBFFB234A0FEFE96009029" bold="true" box="[199,316,351,376]" pageId="7" pageNumber="354">Variation.</emphasis>
Specimens preserved in alcohol can have fore and mid legs paler than hind leg.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
